However if I was to read just  one of the ones that I haven't read - what would you suggest?

So today I had some spare time and made my 4th trip to O2 on Oxford St to complain that yet again they hadn't bothered to contact me about my query 2.5 weeks ago.

I've been polite and understanding everytime I go in. It's a busy store and the staff seem to be constantly run off their feet.

So today I got to the head of the queue and I said really sorry, everytime I've come here I've been refered to your assistant manager . Can you please go and get him. So she asks me to tell her what the problem is and I vented on the poor woman.

Anyway she goes away and drags him back and he's like hasn't this been sorted yet? I told someone to contact you. 

When I explain that yet again no-one has bothered he's very apologetic and heads out the back with my server. 2 mins later she comes back apologises profusely and says that the thing I was waiting for has been ordered and that they will send me a free gift to help take the sting out of their poor customer service. 

So I left expecting to get a free sim card or something equally useless. I get home having forgotton all about it and found these outside my door!



 So have a silly smile on my face and am much happier. 

I never expected to get flowers from O2.

It's been a nice long weekend.

I spent Saturday in class with M doing business maths. I am sure that I didn't do half of this stuff in high school :( So am trying to work out what the text book is saying. I was sure that I would never have to do algebra or equations again. Urgh.

I talked to home yesterday morning and than spent some time  in the park reading the 14th book in the Phryne Fisher series by Australian author Kerry Greenwood. They're mysteries / crime set in 1920's Melbourne. And I've just realised that you can get most of them on Amazon.co.uk. Fab!

I  also watched a few (6) episodes of BSG Series 2 (I need to catch up so I can start going into the magazine section of Forbidden Planet again) and did some knitting while watching it. 

Today I slept in and didn't get out of bed til 11 and that's only cause Scottish Power woke me up. And it's probably a good thing that the answering maching kicked in before I got to the phone. 

I had breakfast and than crawled back into bed with the 15th Phyrne book. I had a hundred pages to go with that when M called and asked if I had started revising maths yet as she had a question.  After I got off the phone I finished Death by Water and spent the rest of the day studying.

I'm now going to have a shower, cook dinner and watch a few more eopisodes of BSG before crawling into bed.

I do wish that the year could have a few more long weekends in them.

So after all my worrying about being deported it's not going to happen. I think that my mum may be a little disapointed. She's still trying to bribe me to come home with puppy's.

Anyway work agreed to pay for new visa a while ago as my old one expires on the 3rd March. And they agreed to pay for the premium service which means in person and 98% decided same day as opposed to postal with minimum 20 working days and 70% decided to 14 weeks 90% decided.

So I was up bright and early this morning to be at Croydon at 8 for my 9 o'clock appointment. I was very impressed with the IND staff as they were cheerful and effcient the whole time I was there.

I arrived at 7.40 (and that was a challenge as the road signs in Croydon are a disgrace) and there was already a queue of about 25 people in front of me. So I pulled out my book and read while I waited.

Dead on 8am the security staff came out and asked who had appointments. Not a single person in front of me did.

I was the 4th person through the door and thanks to

pisica
's security experience was through to the next section of my adventure in no time (Unlike the guy in front of me who couldn't grasp the concept that coins in pockets sets off metal detectors!).

 

I had a paperwork check where I discovered the the person who had booked my appointment had totally got my name wrong - though this didn't matter as I had a reference number. Still! Kelly? I spelt my name twice.

However the very nice lady sorter it out and than sent me upstairs to pay the stupid amount of money they wanted for same day service. And than I was sent upstairs again to wait to be called. (Oh and for the premium service - you can only use the lift if you are disabled.)

This was 8.06! I was called at 8.40 and in 20 mins all was approved (and that's without looking at all the paperwork I took) and I got to go and wait for my visa to be endorsed in my passport. This was the worst bit. The building has less comfort than an airport terminal and is much colder. Metal chairs bolted to the floor and nothing interesting to look at. Good thing I had plenty to read.

This according to the sign on the wall should have taken minimun of 2 hours to endorse in my passport. An hour and 10 mins later I was on my way to work with a 5 year Limited Leave to Remain visa. It's all shiny :)

I didn't think that I would be at work til at least 2pm.

Instead I was in at just past 11. And to make things better my boss has taken an unexpected few days extra leave. It was so very peaceful today.

Come May 08 I can do this all over again to apply for Indefinite Leave to Remain. Since I will have to pay for it I just may go for the postal service.  Anyway that's a worry for another day. As it is I can go to bed quite happily without worrying about what I would do with my books if I had to go home in a hurry.

Today was supposed to be a reasonably lazy day.

The first plan was to sleep in as I've been running around a lot lately and I felt that I needed the sleep.

This was foiled as someone rang me at 9.15.

So I was up and out a lot earlier than planned. I started with Barnes station to get the tickets I need for Monday.

All was going well til the Station assistant realised that she was selling me tickets for today. She sorted it out eventually but there were a lot of people in the queue behind me before she had finished.

I than went to East Sheen to pay my rent, return overdue library books and trawl through the charity shops.

Returning the overdue library books was amusing. I had 4 books out. When I tried to renew them online last week I could only renew 1 as 2 were missing and the other was reserved.

So handed them over and said I think I owe you money. Her reply was you don't!

I argued with her but she was insistent that I didn't owe them anything so I eventually gave up.

After the library I went through 5 charity shops and came out without having purchased a single book! Not one.

This is becoming tedious.

Where are my chalet 1st edition hardbacks in immaculate dustjackets? Oh I did see a Collins Modern Classics of School at the Chalet. I left it there.

So I popped on a bus and went to Stash. I was only planning on buying some 5mm straight Addi's.

However I found these and thought they were fab so they came home with me. I'm sure that this doesn't suprise anyone. 



The fact that I don't know how to knit socks is neither here nor there.

I stayed and had lunch with some of the lady's there. Some of them were from the Liberty's group and than we went back to the store to knit I continued work on the sweater.

After Stash I went around the charity shops in Putney. Nothing again.

Arrived home and the downstairs neighbour came up to measure. I think they are planning on reroofing the roof. Lets hope so as the collection of buckets/vases/bins and a wok on the table just in case it rains is becoming tedious.

Tomorrow plans are to sleep in :) Talk to home. Fill in final application form for visa appointment on Monday and get some passport sized photographs. 

I am sure that there are other things I need to do tomorrow. I just can't think of them at the moment.

Just my luck!

Ran into the boss earlier on the stairs and she was like I hope you don't mind. 

Well it would be rude to say Yes I did and that I really wanted it over and done with today.

Than she followed this up with I haven't filled in your form yet as I never used to have to do these and I don't know what to say.

I can see it being a great meeting.

Anyway it's rescheduled for Thursday between the other 2 she is doing that day.

Bring on Friday is all that I can say.

And thanks for all the good wishes. I feel that I shall need them.

The last day of work before Christmas was very relaxing.

Boss and most of the team were away and if we had to work til 3pm than at least it was better than 5.30.

After I left work I wandered off to HMV's New Year Sale.

I found a copy of the soundtrack from The Hunt for Red October. I last heard this album (on tape) when I was in high school and it was something that I always meant to buy.

Now I have it and Bec's jealous.

I also purchased Best of the Bangles. It just had to be done.

I than wandered off home to wrap the last of the christmas presents and talk to home.

Next day was the trip down to the Isle of Wright to stay with A&A and her family.

The train trip had a bus element and the ferry wasn't as cool as the ones on Sydney Harbour. I was very disappointed that I couldn't go outside. I love sea air blowing in your face. I'd even taken my christmas present from 
pinkhebe
for the purpose.

On the whole though it was a good trip - lots of peace and quiet.

Arrived at Ryde Pierhead where A picked me up and took me to her parents.

Christmas Eve I went with A&A, her Mum and brother J to midnight mass. It was Catholic Church this year and very interesting. As always there was lots of incense flowing round. It's something that I don't seem to be able to get used to.

Christmas morning we all slept in, to be honest we slept in everyday. Very nice.

Present unwrapping came after lunch and there was lots of paper flying around. A's dad tried to stay on top of it but as he had more presents than anyone else it kept escaping.

While I was down there we played lots of board, card & DVD games. The favourite was the new version of Scene It.

I also finally saw all the Wallace and Grommit episodes. I thought there were more than 3. Now I need to see the movie. We also watched the rest of the Hogfather (loved it and want the dvd), the Doctor Who Christmas Special as well as the Christmas Vicar of Dibley and A's favourite the Muppet Christmas Carol.

Oh and the new James Bond. Loved it and want to see it again. Also had great fun playing with Zeke - a main coone and so very furry. If I was on the couch he would have front paws over my shoulder and his tail was way past the diagonal knee.

Thursday I left as had to come home and wash clothes! I washed clothes and rewatched the Mummy and the Mummy Returns. While I was imdbing later I realised that Brandon Fraser is signed to do a currently untitled Rick O'Connell Adventure. I really hope that Rachael Weisz is in it too as they are great together.

Friday morning I woke with a really nasty headache. I spent most of the day asleep til I had to leave to meet 
rosealare
in town.

We had Wong Kei and than headed to her house as we were leaving for York early the next day.

I spent the evening playing with her wool while she packed.

We had a good trip up - we had a little stop at Stamford though we didn't find a lot to buy and arrived at
minniemoll
's just after lunch time.

We than played with her wool (I want stash like hers) and with presents until dinner time.

The next day we headed into York and I managed only to buy a calender. Horses this year as Micheal Whelan doesn't have one out again - maybe next year.

minniemoll
's parents arrived after afternoon tea and were lovely. We had a great time (Minniemoll the food was great - I may just have to come again :) and we managed to stay awake this year til past midnight.

Before mdnight  (with help) I managed to get the hat finished. Unsightly proof is on
rosealare
's lj.

We headed home after lunch the next day. Managed an even quicker trip back as we only stopped at the services. Have also heard that Little Chef is going broke. I am still traumatised by my one and only experience there this time last year so can't say this makes me sad at all.

I stayed the night and we watched the Vicar of Dibley finale - I laughed a lot.

The next day we both headed off to work. Boss and C was away and P went home before lunch ill.

The only other thing that I have to add is that in 2006 I read 348 books and finished knitting 4 items. Not a huge amount of the knitting score - the total maybe better next year.

Pictures of presents are below -
minniemoll
's are missing - I will try to enter them tomorrow.

Well I wrote this last night and than the new improved Explorer 7 ate it!

Had a fantastic night, it was the FEI World Cup Qualifier. My seat was fab - 2nd row in the middle. Also the people on either side of me weren't there. I swear there is more leg room at the ROH. Tonight is supposed to be sold out so am not expecting any leg room at all.

Saw some wonderful horses. My favourite was Sunrise ridden by Imke Schellekens-Bartels.

And also there was Kyra was riding Max and Isabell on Warum Nicht FRH.

My only disappointment of the night was that Anky wasn't riding however she is holding a masterclass tonight.

The newest invention this year is that when you bought your program you received a little radio. They have commentators broadcasting during the performance which was very interesting. Apparantly all the zigzags except for Kyra's were dreadful and there were many disappointing extended walks.

Anyway need to dash to the post office which opens at nine today so I can get these very late parcels in the post!

Today was the day. I had lugged all my books into work today and yesterday, and I met 

rosealare 
 at Forbidden Planet at a few minutes to 6pm.

 

I really like going to author signings but in England they always seem to be unexpected and with little or no publicity. Maybe it's just that going to Australia takes more of an effort than coming to England. This isn't a problem as I get more time to talk to the author but I always feel awful for them when hardly anyone turns up.

Anyway 

rosealare 
 and I had a wander around the store and than headed to the signing table. This was recognizable due to the biggest stack of Sharon Shinn books I have ever seen in my life.

 

I have most of Sharon's books. Some here and some in Australia. Today I may have bought a few that I love but only have copies of in Aus. That's because they are hard to find here generally.

Sharon signed all my books. I didn't have too many :) I have been know to turn up at author signings with more.

I don't mind authors refusing to sign all of my books but some of them will do them all if you ask nicely and don't hog the queue.

Sharon wrote different things in most of the books but my favourite was this:

To Kerri - who has the most books of almost anyone I know! Sharon Shinn.

How cool is that!

On Monday I was supposed to go to Fitness but as it was raining I cancelled. Apparantly they finished a lot earier than normal as it was bucketing down. Instead MJ and I went and had Frozen Margaritas and nachos at Chiquitos.

It was a fun evening - we ended up there as we had been going to see Borat but were told by someone to wait for the dvd.

Last night was the London Chalet Meeting. There were only 16 of us and one person left early.

We had fun at the beginning as I wasn't paying attention when I ordered Lemon, Lime and bitters and received a pint of lemonade and masterbrew bitters (nice). So I took it upstairs with me and tried to palm it off on anyone else. No one was interested and than discovered that her lemonade was actually sparking water. So my bitters was diluted with sparking water. Anyway managed to get them changed for the correct drinks.

There were also many rude comments made about the quiz which I was involved with. 

rosealare 
 and
thesprog 
 
were on the winning team. They have already started organising their quiz for next year.

In other news Sharon Shinn is signing at Forbidden Planet on Thursday. 6-7pm for those who are interested. I dragged half my books in today and will bring the rest in tomorrow. I really enjoy her books but I have no idea on what is coming out next so it will be a good chance to ask. Especially as she doesn't have her own website.

I'm curently reading Witchling by Yasmine Galenorn. It was a little slow to start with but I am half way though and thinking about buying the sequel. It's not the best book I've ever read but it's okay. The sequel isn't out til July next year so it's not like I have to rush and make a decision.

Another weekend has disappeared and I'm not quite sure where it went.

Friday night I had dinner with

rosealareat Wong Kei's. She kindly presented me with my very own Starbucks card. Isn't she sweet!

Saturday I slept in til 9am  - late for me though I know the rest of the world thinks differently. 

I did some housecleaning and than went and met
rosealareat Stash. This time I was after Bec's Xmas present and not only did they not have the items I wanted in stock they also didn't know when they were coming in. Bah. May need to get it online.

Or swop her Xmas and Bday presents around. I already have half of her bday present already. Anyway I managed to leave without spending a cent
rosealare 
was less restrained, and nearly convinced me to follow her example and buy some Lorna's Laces. It certainly gorgeous wool and I would love to play with it but my stash is huge and as I haven't finished anything for a while I think I should before I buy anything else. Haha. We'll see how long that lasts...

We came back to mine and 
rosealare had a good stickybeak and  we consumed the pizza she bought. We than wandered to the Barnes wool store and than headed off to A&A's for their  new dining room tables first dinner party. 

A picked us up from the station and I saw the other A&A who I hadn't seen for a year. M was also there and a great time was had by all. The kittens tried  & suceeded in joining the dinner party. Afterwards we had a game of Star War's Episode 2 monopoly. It was huge fun and nice to play with other people just as ruthless as me :)

We got to bed sometime after 2am as we got distracted by some horrendous music videos. 

Morning came too soon and we all watched Confetti over brunch. I don't think any of us had seen it before. I spent the whole movie trying to think where I had seen the character Sam from. It's finally come to me. She was Bex in According to Bex. Anyway it was a very enjoyable movie and the guy's seemed to like it just as much as the girls.

Left about 3ish and headed home. Was supposed to be seeing Casino Royale tonight with some work collegues but London was booked out. So we will see it during the week.

Instead I came home and curled up on the couch and watched Toy Story 2. It was a birthday gift with Toy Story - so many people where horrified that I had never seen it that it was inevitable that I received it off someone. Anyway loved it just as much as TY. It's odd - I love everything by Pixar except the Incredibles. Maybe I was just in a bad mood when I watched it and I need to watch it again. Everyone else seems to love it.

I'm currently reading Drop Dead Gorgeous for the third time. I really hope that Linda Howard will bring out a third Blair book but don't know that it's feasible. I'll just have to live in hope. 

I also received Evelyn FInds Herself from Girls Gone By and The Winter of Enchantment from fidrabooks. I've been looking forward to both of these so will give an opinion when I have had a chance to read them.

I'm all moved in and exhausted with it.

Everything is unpacked - except for the books.

I have too many things that for sure. Or maybe I should amend that statement to I have too many books.

I know that statement should be considered heresay and if I hadn't moved 36 A4 paper boxes of books I'd agree that it was.

And that's after getting rid of 271! I took them to the local charity shops.

This however leaves me with 840 of them.

There was also 3 boxes of dvd's and 1 of cd's. 

The only thing I can say is that when I move out of here I'm going to have less books. 

My back and arms are as one on that point.

Am going to call mum now and than have a hot bath and crawl into bed.

IAnd i's proving very hard to deal with.

Boss is back from honeymoon and on the warpath. C & I listed all the things I had to do and worked out I have about 3.5 days worth of stuff sitting on the desk. Boss wants it all done by Friday.

Next Wednesday she is sending me to Bath. Have no idea why and C&P at the moment aren't going.  I am really hoping that Boss stays in London too. Boss was in Bath yesterday - I think there is a newer version of Agresso coming so it could be training.

Turns out the netball team continued their winning streak last night with the best win yet. 19-3.

It was such a farce that everyone played their most hated positions for the second half. Next week we play the only team to beat us in the league. Everyone is looking forward to the rematch. 

Amazon has shipped my 2 parcels. One was sent Parcelnet on the 1st and one sent Royal Mail tonight. Any guesses on which order arrives first. I think that I have my money on Royal Mail.

Today also picked up the new Lois McMaster Bujold in Forbidden Planet. Won't read it until the weekend. I may need the distraction after spending the weekend with the  Aunt and Uncle. I did leave them on the other side of the world for a reason. My mother is pleased that they are on this side at the moment and wishes they would stay here. Families - you have to love them.

Am off for a bath and than am planning to crawl into bed with my knitting and watch the last episode of Doc Martin. I'm enjoying Doc Martin but the thought of living in a town like that just about gives me hives.

Having had Friday off as study leave has made me all confused about what day this is. It feels like it should be Monday but it isn't!

So Friday I had a haircut - It's now about an inch longer than my ears - everytime I look in a mirror it's a doubletake. I like it but will like it more when it's longer - it won't take long though as my hair grows at a rate of knots.  I also went food shopping and studied.

Yesterday I tidied the room for the prospective new tenant's visit. I am off to sublet Bettina and Warrens while they are in Africa so they can hang onto their flat.

Afterwards I also put lot's of genre books on the floor that I may be able to live without. Unfortunately a little in to this task I felt guilty for not studying and went back to it. (They are still on the floor - but today (Sunday) the op shop is shut so it will have to wait til tomorrow).

In the evening I went into town and met dozydormouse, pinkhebe, ciorstaidh, HB and SR for dinner. We met at Borders on Oxford St and Pinkhebe yet again sorted out my knitting. And than went to a little Italian place that Pinkhebe introduced us to a while ago and had a very fine meal.

We than wandered down Oxford St, stopping to look at shoes in store windows and depositied SR on the tube and wandered towards home where I crashed into bed and was out like a light. 

Breakfast time now and than I should get down to studying. I'd really rather just lay in the sun and read...

Yes I know I am bad at the whole updating thing. But by the time I work through my friends list - all of whom have much more interesting lives than me, I really don't have much to say.

However in the spirit of at least trying tonight a large group of us caught up with GP and spouse from Victoria. It was a very pleasant evening and such a shame they tossed us out when the shop shut as we than dispersed in different directions.

Many thanks also go to Pinkhebe who double checked my tension square as I wasn't sure that I was counting correctly. I was thanks to rosealare's nifty gadget that she kindly purchased from the bad woolshop in SW London. Back to the sunject at hand though - I have now cast on 100 stitches for the Raglan Sweater with Cable Detail from one of the early Debbie Bliss Noro books. Expect to see the finished product in 50 years or so.

Oh while I'm writing  - if you like Vampire books check out Twilight by Stephanie Meyer - it's YA so not gruesome and is the best book that I have read so far this year. The sequel New Moon is just as good. 

Right am off to hang out the washing, blast my hair with the blowdryer and crawl into bed.

Bec left today.

We spent the night in a Heathrow hotel, it made it so easy this morning.

We arrived at 10pm and checked her in. No excess baggage charge thank goodness and wandered off to get some breakfast.

After it we checked the information boards only to be told her flight was delayed.

Instead of leaving at 12.45 it was leaving at 15.15.

She wasn't happy as this means she will arrive at Sydney at 2am if the plane doesn't make the time up.

Not much that could be done so we wandered around Terminal 3 for hours.

The only exciting thing is that Burger King has gone and there is a Ponti's in it's place.

Ponti's is an Italian kind of panini/salad/pasta place - there's one in Bluewater and London and is great.

After sending Bec through the gate I caught the tube to Hammersmith and met Bettina.

We went and saw Cars on the large Odeon at Leicester Square.

I loved it and would like to see it again.

Afterwards we wandered towards Waterloo - as we passed Trafalgar Square we stopped to see what was going on there.

They are having a festival and I took the following pictures.

just sat on my (empty) wineglass.

It didn't break.

I am very impressed as it didn't break!

I thought that you would like to know....

Had a wonderful day and am now very tired.

Left early (8.30am) and picked up Anna on the way went to a bookstore in North Shields?   and Anna picked up a few things but there wasn't anything there that I really wanted and I don't have the space to buy just because. Scary part was being asked by someone buying something if we were the Brent Dyer ladies? (Ladies? who on earth would call us Ladies!) I had this sudden thought that there were neon lights flashing above our heads!

Than to lunch - Called into a little bakery that   knows of. A cornish pastry and 2 different types of chocolaty cakes came to 2 pounds and a penny.... stunned silence on my part as was expecting about a fiver. Food was fantastic. Good thing it's in the north and I am generally in London or I would roll to work. Ate it in the car over looking the sea and a ruined Abbey. Someone with absolutely no sense built a very ugly coastgaurd building right in front of it, right on the cliff. Some days you just have to wonder.

Then off to the Seven Stories centre for childrens books in Newcastle. Parts of it was very disappointing ie that it is 7 floors, however only 2 had anything interesting. I suppose that it is set up for children and not aduts but still.

Highlight was seeing that parts of the handwritten manuscript for Harry Potter and the Philosphers Stone and drawings that never made it into the book. There must have been parts from different section of the book as they were all on different types of note paper.

There was also original artwork from Paddington, Shirley Hughes, Alan Lee (want!), Joyce Lancaster Brisley, Peter Boston & Quentin Blake and all sorts of others who I can't think of at the moment.

We spent around 2 hours there - had a dig through the attached.childrens bookshop but didn't think that it was as well stocked as it should be. Especially as it touts itself as the largest indepandent childrens bookstore in the country.

Then went into Newcastle itself - had trouble with the roads - they have shut one of the bridges which has thrown the traffic into chaos. Had a wander through some more shops and went down Grey Street. According to   it was voted the best street in Britain by BBC Radio 4 listeners. Didn't get all the way down so maybe we missed something reallty exciting!  

Right now am headed off to bed as lots planned for tomorrow. Lou's shop, maybe Harrogate and somewhere else.

Holidays are really hard work!
